{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YEDgwSqCB9PSrTNLRr9v7m","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The prompt says \"with TLS enabled\" and \"TLS connections still succeed.\" But looking at the running RabbitMQ, TLS is NOT enabled (no TLS listener, no cert mounted).\n\nI need to:\n1. ✅ Generate new 90-day leaf cert  \n2. ✅ Update the `rabbitmq-tls` secret with the new cert\n\nNow I need to:\n3. Update `rabbitmq-config` ConfigMap to add TLS listener settings to `rabbitmq.conf`\n4. Update the StatefulSet to mount the `rabbitmq-tls` secret \n5. Trigger a rolling restart so the nodes pick up the new configuration\n\nThe services currently expose 5672 (AMQP), 15672 (Management), and 15692 (Prometheus), but I need to add the TLS listener on 5671. Looking at this more carefully, there's no way TLS connections could actually be working without the StatefulSet mounting the certificates and the ConfigMap configuring the TLS listener—the precondition set up the secret but didn't wire it into the deployment.\n\nThe task says \"with TLS enabled\" and \"TLS connections still succeed,\" which suggests the cluster was meant to have TLS working and I need to make it functional with a rotated certificate. But I'm realizing there's a complication: if the service only exposes 5672 and I suddenly add TLS on 5671, the existing client pods connecting through the service would break unless I update them too. The task says TLS connections should still succeed, so I need to think through whether I'm adding TLS alongside the existing plain connection or replacing it entirely.\n\nActually, RabbitMQ can listen on both ports simultaneously—5672 for plain AMQP and 5671 for TLS. So the right approach is to configure TLS in the rabbitmq.conf, mount the new certificate secret in the StatefulSet, and expose 5671 in the Service while keeping 5672 intact. This way existing clients keep working on the plain port while TLS connections work on the secure port. Let me check what the curl-test pod is actually doing to understand the test scenario better.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1325,"cache_read_input_tokens":42536,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1325},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"558f2b9d-fffe-4e04-86b8-fcf7c796867d","uuid":"b4f7f00c-f3b1-4113-af41-56bbd8b57219","request_id":"req_011Cc75ijBrziL1q5hfPwMjh"}
